Here is a C++ function that uses regular expressions to convert Markdown to HTML. This function uses the `std::regex` and `std::string` libraries in C++.

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::regex markdownHeadersRegex("^#+ (.*)$", std::regex::icase);
    std::regex italicRegex(@"(\*([^*]|[^\\])\*(|[^\]))
std::regex boldRegex(@"\*{2}([^\*]|[^\\])\*{2}|__([^\_]|[^\\])__");
std::regex linkRegex(@"\[(\S+)\]\(([^)]+)\)");
std::regex imageRegex(@"!?\[(\S+?),\s*\s*\\[\"']?(\S+)?[\"']?\]\s*\(\s*(\S+?)\s*\)");

    html += "<div>";
    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), markdownHeadersRegex); it != std::sregiend(); ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<h" << (match.str(1).size() - 1 << 1 + 1 << ">>" << match.str(1) << "</h" << (match.str(1).size() - 1 << 1 + 1 << ">\n";
    }

    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), italicRegex); it != std::sregiend(); ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<i>" << std::regex_replace(match.str(2), italicRegex, "\\1") << "</i>";
    }

    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), boldRegex); it != std::sregiend(); ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<b>" << std::regex_replace(match.str(2), boldRegex, "\\1") << "</b>";
    }

    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), linkRegex); it != std::sregiend(); ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<a href=\"" << match.str(2) << "\">" << match.str(1) << "</a>";
    }

    for (std::sregex_iterator it(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), imageRegex); it != std::sregiend(); ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        html += "<img src=\"";
        if (!match.str(2).empty()) html += match.str(2);
        else html += match.str(1);
        html += "\" alt=\"" << match.str(1) << "\" title=\"" << match.str(1) << "\" />";
    }

    html += "</div>";
    return html;
}
```
This function converts Markdown headers, italic text, bold text, links, and images to HTML. It's not a full implementation of the Markdown syntax, but it covers some basic and commonly used syntax.

Please note that regular expressions can be complex and tricky to write and maintain. The expressions used in this function may need to be adjusted based on your specific requirements. Additionally, this function does not handle nested constructs (like bold and italic text together) correctly.

Also, this code does not handle errors. For a fully-fledged solution you might want to consider using a Markdown parsing library.

