	* Use a 2D array or a data structure to represent the game board.
2. **Graphics**:
	* Load and display the game assets (images) using your chosen graphics library.
	* Animate the snake's movement by updating the image positions on the screen.
3. **Input Handling**:
	* Handle user input (arrow keys or equivalent) to control the snake's movement.
4. **Game Loop**:
	* Create a game loop that updates the game state, renders the graphics, and handles input.

**SDL Example Code (a minimal setup)**

Here's a basic example using SDL to get you started:
```c
#include <SDL2/SDL.h>
#include <SDL2/SDL_image.h>
#include <stdio.h>

#define WIDTH 640
#define HEIGHT 480

// Game assets
SDL_Texture* snakeTexture;
SDL_Texture* foodTexture;
SDL_Texture* backgroundTexture;

// Game state
int snakeX, snakeY;
int foodX, foodY;
int score;
int speed = 10; // pixels per frame

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    // Initialize SDL
    if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_VIDEO) < 0) {
        printf("SDL initialization failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        return 1;
    }

    // Create a window
    SDL_Window* window = SDL_CreateWindow("Snake Game", SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, SDL_WINDOWPOS_CENTERED, WIDTH, HEIGHT, SDL_WINDOW_SHOWN);
    if (window == NULL) {
        printf("Window creation failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        SDL_Quit();
        return 1;
    }

    // Create a renderer
    SDL_Renderer* renderer = SDL_CreateRenderer(window, -1, SDL_RENDERER_ACCELERATED);
    if (renderer == NULL) {
        printf("Renderer creation failed: %s\n", SDL_GetError());
        SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
        SDL_Quit();
        return 1;
    }

    // Load game assets
    snakeTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "snake.png");
    foodTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "food.png");
    backgroundTexture = IMG_LoadTexture(renderer, "background.png");

    // Main game loop
    while (true) {
        // Handle events
        SDL_Event event;
        while (SDL_PollEvent(&event)) {
            if (event.type == SDL_QUIT) {
                break;
            } else if (event.type == SDL_KEYDOWN) {
                // Handle user input (arrow keys)
                switch (event.key.keysym.sym) {
                    case SDLK_UP:
                        snakeY -= speed;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_DOWN:
                        snakeY += speed;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_LEFT:
                        snakeX -= speed;
                        break;
                    case SDLK_RIGHT:
                        snakeX += speed;
                        break;
                }
            }
        }

        // Update game state
        // ...

        // Clear the screen
        SDL_SetRenderDrawColor(renderer, 0, 0, 0, 255);
        SDL_RenderClear(renderer);

        // Draw game assets
        SDL_Rect snakeRect = {snakeX, snakeY, 20, 20};
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, snakeTexture, NULL, &snakeRect);
        SDL_Rect foodRect = {foodX, foodY, 20, 20};
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, foodTexture, NULL, &foodRect);
        SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, backgroundTexture, NULL, NULL);

        // Update the screen
        SDL_RenderPresent(renderer);

        // Cap the frame rate
        SDL_Delay(1000 / 60); // 60 FPS
    }

    // Clean up
    SDL_DestroyTexture(snakeTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(foodTexture);
    SDL_DestroyTexture(backgroundTexture);
    SDL_DestroyRenderer(renderer);
    SDL_DestroyWindow(window);
    SDL_Quit();
    return 0;
}
```
This example sets up a basic game loop using SDL, loads image assets, and handles user input. You'll need to implement the game logic, collision detection, and scoring mechanics on top of this foundation.

**Additional Tips:**

